# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drone-uav-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Airborne FPV is a type of remote-control (RC) flying that has grown in popularity in recent years.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] It involves mounting a small video camera and an analogue video transmitter to an RC aircraft and flying by means of a live video down-link, commonly displayed on video goggles or a portable monitor.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] FPV became increasingly common throughout the late 2000s and early 2010s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] It is currently one of the fastest growing activities involving RC aircraft, and has given rise to a small but growing industry providing products specifically designed for FPV use.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] FPV aircraft are frequently used for aerial photography and videography, and many videos of FPV flights can be found on popular video sites such as YouTube and Vimeo.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] For this purpose, many FPV pilots utilize a second, lightweight high-definition on-board camcorder in addition to their standard-definition video link(s).
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] A 2021 movie *Red Notice* became one of the first Hollywood feature films to extensively utilize an FPV drone for cinematography.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] There are two primary components of a FPV setup: the airborne component and the ground component (typically called a ground station).
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] A basic FPV system consists of a camera and an analogue video transmitter on the aircraft with a video receiver and a display on the ground.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Another common feature is the addition of pan and tilt capability to the camera, provided by servos.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] This, when coupled with video goggles and "head tracking" devices creates a truly immersive, first-person experience, as if the pilot was actually sitting in the cockpit of the RC aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Receiving equipment—commonly referred to as the "Ground Station"—generally consists of an analog video receiver (matching the frequency of the transmitter on board the aircraft) and a viewing device.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] More complex Ground Stations often include a means to record the received image along with more sophisticated antennas for achieving greater range and clarity.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Any model aircraft can be modified for FPV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The two most common choices are fixed-wing aircraft and multirotors, although early adopters have converted model helicopters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Fixed-wing aircraft are generally medium-sized with sufficient payload space for the video equipment and large wings capable of supporting the extra weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Most have a pusher propeller, allowing a "prop free" image on either the live video feed or the high-definition recording.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Flying wing designs are popular for FPV, as many pilots believe they provide the best combination of large wing surface area, speed, maneuverability, and gliding ability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Multicopters, especially quadcopters, have fast been gaining popularity as agile camera platforms that can take high-quality video while hovering and maneuvering in tight spaces.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] This increase in popularity has come about mainly due to new manufacturing techniques and a reduction in component costs, making this side of the FPV hobby more accessible to a wider audience.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In recent years, FPV Multirotor racing has become a very fast growing branch of the RC hobby, along with larger quads built for long range flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] 900 MHz, 1.2 GHz (amateur radio licensees only), 2.4 GHz, and 5.8 GHz.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Sophisticated setups are capable of achieving a range of 20–30 miles or more, further with the help of extra technologies such as noise-clearing.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In addition to the standard video frequencies, 1.3 GHz and 2.3 GHz have emerged to be used without the interference of the bands on more common and used frequencies such as 2.4 GHz.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] 900 MHz offers long range and better object penetration around trees, large plants, and even buildings.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] However, with this more powerful frequency usually requires a larger antenna - so portability is an issue for some setups.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In many countries a radio operator's licence is required to operate at this frequency so commercialization is difficult.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] On the other end of the spectrum is the 5.8 GHz frequency which has been growing in popularity in recent years.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Hardware for this frequency is extremely cheap, does not require a license to use (under the specified dedicated bands and power outputs) and the antennae are relatively small, allowing for better portability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] This frequency offers great video quality when combined with FPV goggles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] However, this signal has poor signal penetration, especially around dense objects such as water and concrete, so its effective range is limited.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] During the Russo-Ukrainian war, FPV drones, often armed with explosives and used as suicide drones, have seen their use by both sides of the conflict.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Initially, their use was mostly by Ukraine, but later also by Russia.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] For example, the Ukrainian-developed KH-S7 suicide drone could be equipped with up to 1 kilogram of payload over 7 kilometers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] By 2024 and 2025, the technological framework of FPV deployment shifted significantly toward overcoming electronic warfare (EW) countermeasures and implementing automated flight protocols.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] As localized tactical jamming networks became ubiquitous, standard analog and unencrypted digital video signals faced severe degradation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] This forced a rapid transition to dynamic frequency-hopping capabilities, multi-band operations, and the integration of edge-AI computer vision modules.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] These onboard software modules allowed FPV platforms to execute autonomous terminal homing, locking onto targets during the final phase of flight even after a complete loss of operator control or radio signal.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The maximum altitude has been raised to 1,000 feet (300 meters) AGL for aircraft weighing up to 3.5 kg.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In the UK, FPV UK is a not for profit association of hobbyist radio control model aircraft pilots .
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] They have advised the CAA on matters pertaining to FPV flying and the impact of regulation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The legal status of FPV and model aircraft in general under federal aviation law is currently unclear.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] This decision was appealed to the full NTSB.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] It remains unclear what other provisions of the Federal Aviation Regulations are applicable to model aircraft, but it is likely that every regulation applicable to "aircraft" generally would potentially apply under this standard.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In this document, the FAA stated its position that model aircraft flown using FPV video goggles do not satisfy the definitional requirement in Sec.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The notice of interpretation further stated that even model aircraft that do qualify for the Sec.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] There are additional legal implications related to the use of radio frequencies for command and control of FPV aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Licensed amateur radio operators are expressly allowed to use amateur radio frequencies for telecommand of model aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] However, the Federal Communications Commission prohibits using amateur radio frequencies for commercial activity (generally any form of economic gain or for-profit activity).
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The FCC has not yet addressed the issue of creating designated command and control frequencies for commercial unmanned aircraft, and most civilian unmanned aircraft continue to use amateur radio frequencies, even when used for commercial purposes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Though it has not so far pursued any enforcement actions related to use of amateur radio frequencies for commercial unmanned aircraft, the FCC has the authority to levy civil forfeitures and fines into the tens of thousands of dollars for violations of its regulations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Under a 2014 edict from the National Park Service, model aircraft and other unmanned aircraft operations are prohibited on all land administered by the National Park Service, with some exceptions for preexisting model aircraft fields that were established prior to the adoption of this rule.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Because the National Park Service does not have jurisdiction over airspace, which is exclusively governed by the FAA, this rule only applies to unmanned aircraft flown from National Park Service land.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] It does not apply to overflight of National Park Service land by unmanned aircraft operated elsewhere.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] There are a wide variety of state and local laws and ordinances affecting model aircraft in general and FPV specifically.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Many state and local governments restrict or prohibit model aircraft from being flown at local parks.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Some state laws purport to restrict or prohibit aerial photography using unmanned aircraft, though such laws would likely be found invalid if challenged in court due to federal preemption, as the FAA has exclusive regulatory jurisdiction over all aircraft and airspace from the surface up.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Because these restrictions prohibit flying beyond the visual range of the pilot (an ability which many view as the most attractive aspect of FPV), most hobbyists that fly FPV do so outside of regular sanctioned RC clubs' membership and those clubs' flying fields.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] The Canadian equivalent of the AMA, the MAAC, has similar regulations to that of the AMA for FPV piloting.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Drone operations in India are regulated by the DGCA under the Drone Rules 2021, requiring registration of all drones (except Nano 250g) on the Digital Sky Platform for a UIN.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] "No Permission, No Takeoff" (NPNT) is mandatory, requiring digital flight clearance.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] Key limits: 400 ft max altitude, direct line-of-sight only, and no-fly zones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] In Australia the operation of FPV aircraft is subject to laws and regulations regarding radio spectrum use which is enforced by the ACMA (Australian Communications and Media Authority) and the use of airspace as enforced by CASA (Civil Aviation Safety Authority).
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] All unmanned aeronautical activities in Australia are ruled by CASR (Civil Aviation Safety Regulations) Part 101 which includes sections for UAV's and model aircraft among other operations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/first-person-view-radio-control] It is currently under review and new regulations specifically relating to UAV's and model aircraft are anticipated.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] A **gimbal** is a pivoted support that permits rotation of an object about an axis.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] A set of three gimbals, one mounted on the other with orthogonal pivot axes, may be used to allow an object mounted on the innermost gimbal to remain independent of the rotation of its support (e.g. vertical in the first animation).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] For example, on a ship, the gyroscopes, shipboard compasses, stoves, and even drink holders typically use gimbals to keep them upright with respect to the horizon despite the ship's pitching and rolling.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The gimbal suspension used for mounting compasses and the like is sometimes called a **Cardan suspension** after Italian mathematician and physicist Gerolamo Cardano (1501–1576) who described it in detail.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] However, Cardano did not invent the gimbal, nor did he claim to.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The device has been known since antiquity, first described in the 3rd c.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] BC by Philo of Byzantium, although some modern authors support the view that it may not have a single identifiable inventor.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The gimbal was first described by the Greek inventor Philo of Byzantium (280–220 BC).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Philo described an eight-sided ink pot with an opening on each side, which can be turned so that while any face is on top, a pen can be dipped and inked — yet the ink never runs out through the holes of the other sides.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] This was done by the suspension of the inkwell at the center, which was mounted on a series of concentric metal rings so that it remained stationary no matter which way the pot is turned.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In Ancient China, the Han dynasty (202 BC – 220 AD) inventor and mechanical engineer Ding Huan created a gimbal incense burner around 180 AD.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] There is a hint in the writing of the earlier Sima Xiangru (179–117 BC) that the gimbal existed in China since the 2nd century BC.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] There is mention during the Liang dynasty (502–557) that gimbals were used for hinges of doors and windows, while an artisan once presented a portable warming stove to Empress Wu Zetian (r.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Extant specimens of Chinese gimbals used for incense burners date to the early Tang dynasty (618–907), and were part of the silver-smithing tradition in China.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The authenticity of Philo's description of a cardan suspension has been doubted by some authors on the ground that the part of Philo's *Pneumatica* which describes the use of the gimbal survived only in an Arabic translation of the early 9th century.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Thus, as late as 1965, the sinologist Joseph Needham suspected Arab interpolation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] However, Carra de Vaux, author of the French translation which still provides the basis for modern scholars, regards the *Pneumatics* as essentially genuine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The historian of technology George Sarton (1959) also asserts that it is safe to assume the Arabic version is a faithful copying of Philo's original, and credits Philo explicitly with the invention.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] So does his colleague Michael Lewis (2001).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The ancient Roman author Athenaeus Mechanicus, writing during the reign of Augustus (30 BC–14 AD), described the military use of a gimbal-like mechanism, calling it "little ape" (*pithêkion*).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] When preparing to attack coastal towns from the sea-side, military engineers used to yoke merchant-ships together to take the siege machines up to the walls.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] But to prevent the shipborne machinery from rolling around the deck in heavy seas, Athenaeus advises that "you must fix the *pithêkion* on the platform attached to the merchant-ships in the middle, so that the machine stays upright in any angle".
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] After antiquity, gimbals remained widely known in the Near East.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In the Latin West, reference to the device appeared again in the 9th century recipe book called the *Little Key of Painting'* (*mappae clavicula*).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The French inventor Villard de Honnecourt depicts a set of gimbals in his sketchbook (see right).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In the early modern period, dry compasses were suspended in gimbals.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In inertial navigation, as applied to ships and submarines, a minimum of three gimbals are needed to allow an inertial navigation system (stable table) to remain fixed in inertial space, compensating for changes in the ship's yaw, pitch, and roll.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In this application, the inertial measurement unit (IMU) is equipped with three orthogonally mounted gyros to sense rotation about all axes in three-dimensional space.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The gyro outputs are kept to a null through drive motors on each gimbal axis, to maintain the orientation of the IMU.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] To accomplish this, the gyro error signals are passed through "resolvers" mounted on the three gimbals, roll, pitch and yaw.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] These resolvers perform an automatic matrix transformation according to each gimbal angle, so that the required torques are delivered to the appropriate gimbal axis.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The yaw torques must be resolved by roll and pitch transformations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Similar sensing platforms are used on aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In inertial navigation systems, gimbal lock may occur when vehicle rotation causes two of the three gimbal rings to align with their pivot axes in a single plane.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] When this occurs, it is no longer possible to maintain the sensing platform's orientation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In spacecraft propulsion, rocket engines are generally mounted on a pair of gimbals to allow a single engine to vector thrust about both the pitch and yaw axes; or sometimes just one axis is provided per engine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] To control roll, twin engines with differential pitch or yaw control signals are used to provide torque about the vehicle's roll axis.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Gimbals are also used to mount everything from small camera lenses to large photographic telescopes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] In portable photography equipment, single-axis gimbal heads are used in order to allow a balanced movement for camera and lenses.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] This proves useful in wildlife photography as well as in any other case where very long and heavy telephoto lenses are adopted: a gimbal head rotates a lens around its center of gravity, thus allowing for easy and smooth manipulation while tracking moving subjects.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Very large gimbal mounts in the form 2 or 3 axis altitude-altitude mounts are used in satellite photography for tracking purposes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Gyrostabilized gimbals which house multiple sensors are also used for airborne surveillance applications including airborne law enforcement, pipe and power line inspection, mapping, and ISR (intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance).
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Sensors include thermal imaging, daylight, low light cameras as well as laser range finder, and illuminators.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Gimbal systems are also used in scientific optics equipment.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] For example, they are used to rotate a material sample along an axis to study their angular dependence of optical properties.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Handheld 3-axis gimbals are used in stabilization systems designed to give the camera operator the independence of handheld shooting without camera vibration or shake.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] There are two versions of such stabilization systems: mechanical and motorized.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Mechanical gimbals have the sled, which includes the top *stage* where the camera is attached, the *post* which in most models can be extended, with the monitor and batteries at the bottom to counterbalance the camera weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] This is how the Steadicam stays upright, by simply making the bottom slightly heavier than the top, pivoting at the gimbal.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] This leaves the center of gravity of the whole rig, however heavy it may be, exactly at the operator's fingertip, allowing deft and finite control of the whole system with the lightest of touches on the gimbal.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Powered by three brushless motors, motorized gimbals have the ability to keep the camera level on all axes as the camera operator moves the camera.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] An inertial measurement unit (IMU) responds to movement and utilizes its three separate motors to stabilize the camera.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] With the guidance of algorithms, the stabilizer is able to notice the difference between deliberate movement such as pans and tracking shots from unwanted shake.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] This allows the camera to seem as if it is floating through the air, an effect achieved by a Steadicam in the past.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Gimbals can be mounted to cars and other vehicles such as drones, where vibrations or other unexpected movements would make tripods or other camera mounts unacceptable.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The rate of a mechanical marine chronometer is sensitive to its orientation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Because of this, chronometers were normally mounted on gimbals, in order to isolate them from the rocking motions of a ship at sea.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] A drone gimbal system is a stabilization mechanism that uses electric motors (usually using brushless servo motors) in the yaw, pitch, and roll axes to isolate the camera or sensor payload from the motion and vibration of the drone.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The system ensures the camera remains stable at a set level, resulting in smooth, high-quality footage even during fast maneuvers or windy conditions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The system relies on an inertial measurement unit (IMU) to accurately estimate the motion and orientation of the drone and a gimbal control unit (GCU), which use IMU data and PID control algorithms to dynamically adjust the motors in real time, canceling out disturbances.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Gimbal lock is the loss of one degree of freedom in a three-dimensional, three-gimbal mechanism that occurs when the axes of two of the three gimbals are driven into a parallel configuration, "locking" the system into rotation in a degenerate two-dimensional space.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] The word "lock" is misleading: no gimbal is restrained; all three gimbals can still rotate freely about their respective axes of suspension.
[src:drone-uav-systems/gimbal] Nevertheless, because of the parallel orientation of two of the gimbals' axes, there is no gimbal available to accommodate rotation about one axis.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] GCS hardware refers to the complete set of ground-based hardware systems used to control the UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] This typically includes the Human-Machine Interface, computer, telemetry, video capture card and aerials for the control, video and data links to the UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Larger military UAVs such as the General Atomics MQ-1 Predator feature what resembles a "virtual cockpit".
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] The pilot or sensor operator sits in front of a number of screens showing the view from the UAV, a map screen and aircraft instrumentation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Control is through a conventional aircraft-style joystick and throttle, possibly with Hands on Throttle and Stick (HOTAS) functionality.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] In addition, the GCS consists of satellite or long-range communication links that are mounted on the roof or on a separate vehicle, container or building.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Smaller UAVs can be operated with a traditional "twin-stick" style transmitter, as used for radio controlled model aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Extending this setup with a laptop or tablet computer, data and video telemetry, and aerials, creates what is effectively a Ground Control Station.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] A number of suppliers offer a combined system that consists of what looks like a modified transmitter combined with what is usually a touch screen.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] An internal computer running the GCS software sits behind the screen, along with the video and data links.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Larger GCS units are also available that typically fit inside flight cases.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] As with the smaller units, they feature an internal computer running the GCS software, along with video and data links.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Large single or dual screens are also fitted that can be high-brightness or treated with an anti-glare coating to increase visibility in bright sunlight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] They can either be placed on the ground, on a portable table, or feature integrated folding legs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] Some portable GCS units are in the HOTAS (Hands On Throttle And Stick) layout.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] This layout includes a 3-Axis Joystick to control yaw, pitch and roll of the UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] A slide or t-bar fader can increase or decrease the airspeed of the UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] GCS software is typically run on a ground-based computer that is used for planning and flying a mission.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] It provides a map screen where the user can define waypoints for the flight, and see the progress of the mission.
[src:drone-uav-systems/ground-control-station] It also serves as a “virtual cockpit”, showing many of the same instruments as in manned aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] A **micro air vehicle** (**MAV**), or **micro aerial vehicle**, is a class of man-portable miniature UAVs whose size enables them to be used in low-altitude, close-in support operations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Modern MAVs can be as small as 5 centimeters - compare Nano Air Vehicle.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Development is driven by commercial, research, government, and military organizations; with insect-sized aircraft reportedly expected in the future.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The small craft allow remote observation of hazardous environments or of areas inaccessible to ground vehicles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Hobbyists have designed MAVs for applications such as aerial robotics contests and aerial photography.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] MAVs can offer autonomous modes of flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] In 2008, the TU Delft University in the Netherlands developed the smallest ornithopter fitted with a camera, the DelFly Micro, the third version of the DelFly project that started in 2005.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] This version measures 10 centimeters and weighs 3 grams, slightly larger (and noisier) than the dragonfly on which it was modeled.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The importance of the camera lies in remote control when the DelFly is out of sight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] However, this version has not yet been successfully tested outside, although it performs well indoors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] He says fly-size ornithopters should be possible, provided the tail is well designed.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Rick Ruijsink of TU Delft cites battery weight as the biggest problem; the lithium-ion battery in the DelFly micro, at one gram, constitutes a third of the weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Luckily, developments in this area are still going very fast, due to the demand in various other commercial fields.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Ruijsink says the purpose of these crafts is to understand insect flight and to provide practical uses, such as flying through cracks in concrete to search for earthquake victims or exploring radioactivity-contaminated buildings.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Spy agencies and the military also see potential for such small vehicles as spies and scouts.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Robert Wood at Harvard University developed an even smaller ornithopter, at just 3 centimeters, but this craft is not autonomous in that it gets its power through a wire.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The group has achieved controlled hovering flight in 2013 as well as landings on and takeoffs from different overhangs in 2016 (both inside a motion tracking environment).
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The **T-Hawk MAV**, a ducted fan VTOL Micro-UAV, was developed by the United States company Honeywell and entered service in 2007.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] This MAV is used by the US Army and US Navy Explosive Ordnance Division to search areas for roadside bombs and inspect targets.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The device was also deployed at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant in Japan to provide video and radioactivity readings after the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] In early 2008, Honeywell received FAA approval to operate its MAV, designated as *gMAV* in the national airspace on an experimental basis.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The gMAV is the fourth MAV to receive such approval.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The Honeywell gMAV uses ducted thrust for lift, allowing it to take off and land vertically and to hover.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] It is also capable of "high-speed" forward flight, according to the company, but no performance figures have been released.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The company also states that the machine is light enough to be carried by a man.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] It was originally developed as part of a DARPA program, and its initial application is expected to be with the police department of Miami-Dade County, Florida.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] In January 2010, Tamkang University (TKU) in Taiwan realized autonomous control of flight altitude of an 8-gram, 20-centimeter wide, flapping-wing MAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The MEMS (MICRO-ELECTRO-MECHANICAL SYSTEMS) Lab of TKU had been developing MAVs for several years, and in 2007 the Space and Flight Dynamics (SFD) Lab joined the research team for the development of autonomous flight MAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Instead of traditional sensors and computational devices, which are too heavy for most MAVs, the SFD combined a stereo-vision system with a ground station to control the flight altitude, making it the first flapping-wing MAV under 10 grams that realized autonomous flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] In 2012, the British Army deployed the sixteen gram Black Hornet Nano Unmanned Air Vehicle to Afghanistan to support infantry operations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Although there are currently no true MAVs (i.e., truly micro scaled flyers) in existence, DARPA has attempted a program to develop even smaller Nano Air Vehicles (NAVs) with a wingspan of 7.5 centimeters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] However, no NAVs meeting DARPA's original program specification were forthcoming until 2009 when AeroVironment demonstrated a controlled hovering of DARPA's flapping-wing NAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Beyond the difficulties in developing MAVs, few designs adequately address control issues.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The MAVs' small size makes teleoperation impractical because a ground station pilot cannot see it beyond 100 meters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] An onboard camera allowing the ground pilot to stabilize and navigate the craft was first demonstrated in the Aerovironment Black Widow, but truly micro air vehicles cannot carry onboard transmitters powerful enough to allow for teleoperation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] For this reason, some researchers have focused on fully autonomous MAV flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] One such device, which has been designed from its inception as a fully autonomous MAV, is the biologically-inspired Entomopter originally developed at the Georgia Institute of Technology under a DARPA contract by Robert C.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Given that MAVs can be controlled by autonomous means, significant test and evaluation issues continue to exist.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Some of the problems that might be encountered in physical vehicles are being approached through simulations of these models.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Limited flight duration is another limitation these vehicles face.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] This is especially true for vehicles weighing less than 10 grams, which are constrained to 10 minute flights.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Solar-powered MAVs are a potential solution, but payload capacity and poor trade-offs between lift generation and power efficiency reduce their viability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] (2024) hit upon a vehicle that could subvert these limitations, which they named the CoulombFly.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] The CoulombFly weighs 4.21 grams, yet can achieve 1 hour flights.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] This is realized with "an electrostatic-driven propulsion system with a high lift-to-power efficiency of 30.7 g W−1 and an ultralight kilovolt power system with a low power consumption of 0.568 W".
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] A new trend in the MAV community is to take inspiration from flying insects or birds to achieve unprecedented flight capabilities.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Biological systems are not only interesting to MAV engineers for their use of unsteady aerodynamics with flapping wings; they are increasingly inspiring engineers for other aspects such as distributed sensing and acting, sensor fusion and information processing.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Recent research within the USAF has focused on development of bird like perching mechanism.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] A ground mobility and perching mechanism inspired from bird claws was recently developed by Vishwa Robotics and MIT and sponsored by US Air Force Research Laboratory.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Various symposia bringing together biologists and aerial roboticists have been held with increasing frequency since 2000 and some books have recently been published on this topic.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Bio-inspiration has been also used in design of methods for stabilization and control of systems of multiple MAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/micro-air-vehicle] Researchers took inspiration from observed behaviors of schools of fish and flocks of birds to control artificial swarms of MAVs and from rules observed in groups of migratory birds to stabilize compact MAV formations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] In a commercial context (i.e., an airline or air freight carrier), payload may refer only to revenue-generating cargo or paying passengers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] A payload of ordnance carried by a combat aircraft is sometimes alternatively referred to as the aircraft's **warload**.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] For a rocket, the payload can be a satellite, space probe, or spacecraft carrying humans, animals, or cargo.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] For a ballistic missile, the payload is one or more warheads and related systems; their total weight is referred to as the throw-weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The fraction of payload to the total liftoff weight of the air or spacecraft is known as the "payload fraction".
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] When the weight of the payload and fuel are considered together, it is known as the "useful load fraction".
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] In spacecraft, "mass fraction" is normally used, which is the ratio of payload to everything else, including the rocket structure.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] There is a natural trade-off between the payload and the range of an aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] A payload range diagram (also known as the "elbow chart") illustrates the trade-off.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The top horizontal line represents the maximum payload.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] It is limited structurally by maximum zero-fuel weight (MZFW) of the aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Maximum payload is the difference between maximum zero-fuel weight and operational empty weight (OEW).
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Moving left-to-right along the line shows the constant maximum payload as the range increases.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] More fuel needs to be added for more range.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The vertical line represents the range at which the combined weight of the aircraft, maximum payload and needed fuel reaches the maximum take-off weight (MTOW) of the aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] If the range is increased beyond that point, payload has to be sacrificed for fuel.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The maximum take-off weight is limited by a combination of the maximum net power of the engines and the lift/drag ratio of the wings.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The diagonal line after the range-at-maximum-payload point shows how reducing the payload allows increasing the fuel (and range) when taking off with the maximum take-off weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The second kink in the curve represents the point at which the maximum fuel capacity is reached.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Flying further than that point means that the payload has to be reduced further, for an even lesser increase in range.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The absolute range is thus the range at which an aircraft can fly with maximum possible fuel without carrying any payload.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] For aircraft, the weight of fuel in wing tanks does not contribute as significantly to the bending moment of the wing as does weight in the fuselage.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] So even when the airplane has been loaded with its maximum payload that the wings can support, it can still carry a significant amount of fuel.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Launch and transport system differ not only on the payload that can be carried but also in the stresses and other factors placed on the payload.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The payload must not only be lifted to its target, it must also arrive safely, whether elsewhere on the surface of the Earth or a specific orbit.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] To ensure this the payload, such as a warhead or satellite, is designed to withstand certain amounts of various types of "punishment" on the way to its destination.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Most rocket payloads are fitted within a payload fairing to protect them against dynamic pressure of high-velocity travel through the atmosphere, and to improve the overall aerodynamics of the launch vehicle.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Most aircraft payloads are carried within the fuselage for similar reasons.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Outsize cargo may require a fuselage with unusual proportions, such as the Super Guppy.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] The various constraints placed on the launch system can be roughly categorized into those that cause physical damage to the payload and those that can damage its electronic or chemical makeup.
[src:drone-uav-systems/payload-air-and-space-craft] Electrical, chemical, or biological payloads can be damaged by extreme temperatures (hot or cold), rapid changes in temperature or pressure, contact with fast moving air streams causing ionization, and radiation exposure from cosmic rays, the van Allen belt, or solar wind.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] A **quadcopter**, also called **quadrocopter**, or **quadrotor** is a type of helicopter or multicopter that has four rotors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Although quadrotor helicopters and convertiplanes have long been flown experimentally, the configuration remained a curiosity until the arrival of the modern unmanned aerial vehicle or drone.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The small size and low inertia of drones allows use of a particularly simple flight control system, which has greatly increased the practicality of the small quadrotor in this application.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Each rotor produces both lift and torque about its center of rotation, as well as drag opposite to the vehicle's direction of flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Quadcopters generally have two rotors spinning clockwise (CW) and two counterclockwise (CCW).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Flight control is provided by independent variation of the speed and hence lift and torque of each rotor.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Pitch and roll are controlled by varying the net centre of thrust, with yaw controlled by varying the net torque.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Unlike conventional helicopters, quadcopters do not usually have cyclic pitch control, in which the angle of the blades varies dynamically as they turn around the rotor hub.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In the early days of flight, quadcopters (then referred to either as *quadrotors* or simply as *helicopters*) were seen as a possible solution to some of the persistent problems in vertical flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Torque-induced control issues (as well as efficiency issues originating from the tail rotor, which generates no useful lift) can be eliminated by counter-rotation, and the relatively short blades are much easier to construct.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] A number of manned designs appeared in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] These vehicles were among the first successful heavier-than-air vertical take off and landing (VTOL) vehicles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] However, early prototypes suffered from poor performance, and latter prototypes required too much pilot work load, due to poor stability augmentation and limited control authority.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] If all four rotors are spinning at the same angular velocity, with two rotating clockwise and two counterclockwise, the net torque about the yaw axis is zero, which means there is no need for a tail rotor as on conventional helicopters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Yaw is induced by mismatching the balance in aerodynamic torques (i.e., by offsetting the cumulative thrust commands between the counter-rotating blade pairs).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] All quadcopters are subject to normal rotorcraft aerodynamics, including the vortex ring state.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The main mechanical components are a fuselage or frame, the four rotors (either fixed-pitch or variable-pitch), and motors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] For best performance and simplest control algorithms, the motors and propellers are equidistant.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In order to allow more power and stability at reduced weight, a quadcopter, like any other multirotor can employ a coaxial rotor configuration.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In this case, each arm has two motors running in opposite directions (one facing up and one facing down).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The quadcopter configuration is relatively simple to program for autonomous flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] This has allowed experiments with complex swarming behaviour based on basic sensing of the adjacent drones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The longest flight time achieved by a battery-powered quadcopter was 2 hours, 31 minutes and 30 seconds.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The record was set by Ferdinand Kickinger of Germany in 2016.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In setting the record, Kickinger used low discharge-rate, high-capacity lithium-ion batteries and stripped the airframe of non-essential weight to reduce power draw and extend endurance.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Alternative power sources like hydrogen fuel cells and hybrid gas-electric generators have been used to dramatically extend endurance because of the increased energy density of both hydrogen and gasoline, respectively.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The fastest speed achieved by a quadcopter is 685 km/h (426 mph) by Benjamin Biggs and Aidan Kelly in Australia on 20 May 2026.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The progression of the Guinness World Record is shown below.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] A record is done by taking the average of two 100m runs in level flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The two runs must be done in opposing directions to account for wind.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The first heavier-than-air aerodyne to take off vertically was a four-rotor helicopter designed by Louis Breguet.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] It was tested only in tethered flight and to an altitude of a few feet.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In 1908 it was reported as having flown 'several times', although details are sparse.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Etienne Oehmichen experimented with rotorcraft designs in the 1920s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Among the designs he tried was the Oehmichen No.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] 2, which employed four two-blade rotors and eight propellers, all driven by a single engine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The angle of the rotor blades could be varied by warping.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Five of the propellers, spinning in the horizontal plane, stabilized the machine laterally.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Another propeller was mounted at the nose for steering.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The remaining pair of propellers functioned as its forward propulsion.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The aircraft exhibited a considerable degree of stability and increase in control-accuracy for its time, and made over a thousand test flights during the middle 1920s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] By 1923 it was able to remain airborne for several minutes at a time, and on April 14, 1924, it established the first-ever FAI distance record for helicopters of 360 m (390 yd).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] It demonstrated the ability to complete a circular course and later, it completed the first 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) closed-circuit flight by a rotorcraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] George de Bothezat and Ivan Jerome developed the de Bothezat helicopter, with six-bladed rotors at the end of an X-shaped structure.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Two small propellers with variable pitch were used for thrust and yaw control.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The vehicle used collective pitch control.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Built by the United States Army Air Service, it made its first flight in October 1922.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] About 100 flights were made by the end of 1923.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The highest it ever reached was about 5 m (16 ft 5 in).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Although demonstrating feasibility, it was underpowered, unresponsive, mechanically complex and susceptible to reliability problems.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Pilot workload was too high during hover to attempt lateral motion.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Convertawings Model A Quadrotor was intended to be the prototype for a line of much larger civil and military helicopters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The design featured two engines driving four rotors through a system of v belts.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] No tail rotor was needed and control was obtained by varying the thrust between rotors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Flown many times from 1956, this helicopter proved the quadrotor design and it was also the first four-rotor helicopter to demonstrate successful forward flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Due to a lack of orders for commercial or military versions however, the project was terminated.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Convertawings proposed a Model E that would have a maximum weight of 42,000 lb (19 t) with a payload of 10,900 lb (4.9 t) over 300 miles and at up to 173 mph (278 km/h).
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Hanson Elastic Articulated (EA) bearingless rotor grew out of work done in the early 1960s at Lockheed California by Thomas F.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Hanson, who had previously worked at Convertawings on the quadrotor's rotor design and control system.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Gloster Crop Sprayer project of 1960 was an early example of a quadcopter drone.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] To be powered by a 105 hp Potez 4E air-cooled flat four-cylinder engine, its 20 gal payload was discharged through a 22 ft spray boom.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Two operators carried homing beacons at opposite ends of the spray run, so that the quadcopter would always home in on a beacon and not overshoot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] However, despite the much simplified design and operational requirements compared to a piloted machine, the parent company board refused to develop it and it remained a paper project.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Curtiss-Wright VZ-7 of 1958 was a VTOL aircraft designed by Curtiss-Wright in competition for the U.S.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Army Transport and Research Command "flying jeep".
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The VZ-7 was controlled by changing the thrust of each of the four ducted fan rotors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Piasecki PA-97 was a proposal for a large hybrid aircraft in which four helicopter fuselages were combined with a lighter-than-air airship in the 1980s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The Bell Boeing Quad TiltRotor concept takes the fixed quadcopter concept further by combining it with the tilt rotor concept for a proposed C-130 sized military transport.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Airbus is developing a battery-powered quadcopter to act as an urban air taxi, at first with a pilot but potentially autonomous in the future.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In the first decades of the 2000s, the quadcopter layout has become popular for small-scale unmanned aerial vehicles or drones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The need for aircraft with greater maneuverability and hovering ability has led to a rise in quadcopter research.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] The four-rotor design allows quadcopters to be relatively simple in design yet highly reliable and maneuverable.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Research is continuing to increase the abilities of quadcopters by making advances in multi-craft communication, environment exploration, and maneuverability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] If these developing qualities can be combined, quadcopters would be capable of advanced autonomous missions that are currently not possible with other vehicles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Around 2005 to 2010, advances in electronics allowed the production of cheap lightweight flight controllers, accelerometers (IMU), global positioning system and cameras.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] This resulted in the quadcopter configuration becoming popular for small unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] With their small size and maneuverability, these quadcopters can be flown indoors as well as outdoors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] For small drones, quadcopters are cheaper and more durable than conventional helicopters due to their mechanical simplicity.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Their smaller blades are also advantageous because they possess less kinetic energy, reducing their ability to cause damage.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] For small-scale quadcopters, this makes the vehicles safer for close interaction.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] It is also possible to fit quadcopters with guards that enclose the rotors, further reducing the potential for damage.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] However, as size increases, fixed propeller quadcopters develop disadvantages relative to conventional helicopters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Increasing blade size increases their momentum.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] This means that changes in blade speed take longer, which negatively impacts control.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Helicopters do not experience this problem as increasing the size of the rotor disk does not significantly impact the ability to control blade pitch.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Due to their ease of construction and control, quadcopters are popular as amateur model aircraft projects.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Throughout the 21st century, there have been reported cases of quadcopter drones being used for criminal activity.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Due to the construction of the Mexico–United States border wall, some drug cartels have resorted to the use of quadcopters to smuggle drugs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] However, quadcopter drones do not necessarily only smuggle drugs across the border, but there are also cases where weapons and other prohibited items are smuggled into prisons around the world.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] Quadcopter drone crime is also occurring in Europe.
[src:drone-uav-systems/quadcopter] In August 2021, a police officer in the Czech Republic seized a quadcopter that was transporting a sachet of methamphetamine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] An **unmanned aerial vehicle** (**UAV**), or **unmanned aircraft system** (**UAS**), commonly known as an **aerial drone** or simply **drone**, is an aircraft with no human pilot, crew, or passengers on board, which instead is either autonomous or controlled remotely.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs were originally developed through the twentieth century for military missions too "dull, dirty or dangerous" for humans, and by the twenty-first had become essential assets to most militaries.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] As control technologies improved and costs fell, their use expanded to many non-military applications.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These include aerial photography, area coverage, precision agriculture, forest fire monitoring, river monitoring, environmental monitoring, weather observation, policing and surveillance, infrastructure inspections, smuggling, product deliveries, entertainment, and drone racing.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Many terms are used for aircraft which fly without any persons on board.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs and RPAVs can also be seen as components of **unmanned aircraft systems** (**UAS**s), which also include ground-based controllers and systems of communications with the aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] *UAS* was adopted by the United States Department of Defense (DoD) and the United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in 2005 according to their Unmanned Aircraft System Roadmap 2005–2030.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) and the British Civil Aviation Authority adopted this term, also used in the European Union's Single European Sky (SES) Air Traffic Management (ATM) Research (SESAR Joint Undertaking) roadmap for 2020.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This term emphasizes the importance of elements other than the aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] It includes elements such as ground control stations, data links and other support equipment.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Similar terms are ***unmanned aircraft vehicle system*** (***UAVS***) and ***remotely piloted aircraft system*** (***RPAS***).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In common usage, *drone* is often applied to both military and civilian UAVs, while technical and regulatory documents may prefer terms such as *UAV*, *UAS*, *RPAS*, or *uncrewed aircraft*.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The term *drone* has been used from the early days of aviation, sometimes being applied to remotely flown target aircraft used for practice firing of a battleship's guns, such as the 1920s Fairey Queen biplane floatplane and 1930s de Havilland Queen Bee biplane.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Later examples included the Airspeed Queen Wasp and Miles Queen Martinet, before ultimate replacement by the GAF Jindivik.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The term *uncrewed* is sometimes used rather than *unmanned* when referring to UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Autonomous drones also employ various advanced technologies to carry out their missions without human intervention, such as cloud computing, computer vision, artificial intelligence, machine learning, deep learning, and thermal sensors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For recreational uses, an aerial photography drone has first-person video, autonomous capabilities, or both.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs may be classified like any other aircraft, according to design configuration such as weight or engine type, maximum flight altitude, degree of operational autonomy, operational role, etc.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Drones can also be classified based on the degree of autonomy in their flight operations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] ICAO classifies unmanned aircraft as either remotely piloted aircraft or fully autonomous.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Some UAVs offer intermediate degrees of autonomy.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For example, a vehicle may be remotely piloted in most contexts but have an autonomous return-to-base operation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Some aircraft types may optionally fly manned or as UAVs, which may include manned aircraft transformed into manned or optionally piloted UAVs (OPVs).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The flight of UAVs may operate under remote control by a human operator, as **remotely piloted aircraft** (**RPA**), or with various degrees of autonomy, such as autopilot assistance, up to fully autonomous aircraft that have no provision for human intervention.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] An example of classification based on the composite criteria is U.S.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Military's unmanned aerial systems (UAS) classification of UAVs based on weight, maximum altitude and speed of the UAV component.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs can be classified based on their power or energy source, which significantly impacts their flight duration, range, and environmental impact.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The earliest recorded use of an unmanned aerial vehicle for warfighting occurred in July 1849, with a balloon carrier (the precursor to the aircraft carrier) in the first offensive use of air power in naval aviation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Austrian forces besieging Venice attempted to launch some 200 incendiary balloons at the besieged city.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The balloons were launched mainly from land; however, some were also launched from the Austrian ship SMS *Vulcano*.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] At least one bomb fell in the city; however, due to the wind changing after launch, most of the balloons missed their target, and some drifted back over Austrian lines and the launching ship *Vulcano*.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The Spanish engineer Leonardo Torres Quevedo introduced a radio-based control-system called the *Telekino* at the Paris Academy of Science in 1903, as a way of testing airships without risking human life.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Significant development of drones started in the 1900s, and originally focused on providing practice targets for training military personnel.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The earliest attempt at a powered UAV was A.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Low confirmed that Geoffrey de Havilland's monoplane was the one that flew under control on 21 March 1917 using his radio system.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Other British unmanned developments followed, leading to the fleet of over 400 de Havilland 82 Queen Bee aerial targets that went into service in 1935.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Nikola Tesla described a fleet of uncrewed aerial combat vehicles in 1915.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These developments also inspired the construction of the Kettering Bug by Charles Kettering from Dayton, Ohio and the Hewitt-Sperry Automatic Airplane – initially meant as an uncrewed plane that would carry an explosive payload to a predetermined target.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Development continued during World War I, when the Dayton-Wright Airplane Company invented a pilotless aerial torpedo that would explode at a preset time.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The film star and model-airplane enthusiast Reginald Denny developed the first scaled remote piloted vehicle in 1935.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Soviet researchers experimented with controlling Tupolev TB-1 bombers remotely in the late 1930s.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 1940, Reginald Denny started the Radioplane Company and more models emerged during World War II – used both to train antiaircraft gunners and to fly attack-missions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Nazi Germany produced and used various UAV aircraft during the war, like the Argus As 292 and the V-1 flying bomb with a jet engine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Fascist Italy developed a specialised drone version of the Savoia-Marchetti SM.79 flown by remote control, although the Armistice with Italy was enacted prior to any operational deployment.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] After World War II development continued in vehicles such as the American JB-4 (using television/radio-command guidance), the Australian GAF Jindivik and Teledyne Ryan Firebee I of 1951, while companies like Beechcraft offered their Model 1001 for the U.S.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Nevertheless, they were little more than remote-controlled airplanes until the Vietnam War.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Air Force, concerned about losing pilots over hostile territory, began planning for the use of uncrewed aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Planning intensified after the Soviet Union shot down a U-2 in 1960.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Within days, a highly classified UAV program started under the code name of "Red Wagon".
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The August 1964 clash in the Tonkin Gulf between naval units of the U.S. and the North Vietnamese Navy initiated America's highly classified UAVs (Ryan Model 147, Ryan AQM-91 Firefly, Lockheed D-21) into their first combat missions of the Vietnam War.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] When the Chinese government showed photographs of downed U.S.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs via *Wide World Photos*, the official U.S. response was "no comment".
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] During the War of Attrition (1967–1970) in the Middle East, Israeli intelligence tested the first tactical UAVs installed with reconnaissance cameras, which successfully returned photos from across the Suez Canal.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This was the first time that tactical UAVs that could be launched and landed on any short runway (unlike the heavier jet-based UAVs) were developed and tested in battle.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In the 1973 Yom Kippur War, Israel used UAVs as decoys to spur opposing forces into wasting expensive anti-aircraft missiles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] After the 1973 Yom Kippur War, a few key people from the team that developed this early UAV joined a small startup company that aimed to develop UAVs into a commercial product, eventually purchased by Tadiran and leading to the development of the first Israeli UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 1973, the U.S. military officially confirmed that they had been using UAVs in Southeast Asia (Vietnam).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Over 5,000 U.S. airmen had been killed and over 1,000 more were missing or captured.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The USAF 100th Strategic Reconnaissance Wing flew about 3,435 UAV missions during the war at a cost of about 554 UAVs lost to all causes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Brown, Commander, Air Force Systems Command, in 1972, "The only reason we need (UAVs) is that we don't want to needlessly expend the man in the cockpit." Later that year, General John C.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] During the 1973 Yom Kippur War, Soviet-supplied surface-to-air missile-batteries in Egypt and Syria caused heavy damage to Israeli fighter jets.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] As a result, Israel developed the IAI Scout as the first UAV with real-time surveillance.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The images and radar decoys provided by these UAVs helped Israel to completely neutralize the Syrian air defenses at the start of the 1982 Lebanon War, resulting in no pilots downed.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In Israel in 1987, UAVs were first used as proof-of-concept of super-agility, post-stall controlled flight in combat-flight simulations that involved tailless, stealth-technology-based, three-dimensional thrust vectoring flight-control, and jet-steering.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] With the maturing and miniaturization of applicable technologies in the 1980s and 1990s, interest in UAVs grew within the higher echelons of the U.S. military.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The U.S. funded the Counterterrorism Center (CTC) within the CIA, which sought to fight terrorism with the aid of modernized drone technology.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] DoD gave a contract to AAI Corporation along with Israeli company Malat.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Navy bought the AAI Pioneer UAV that AAI and Malat developed jointly.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Many of these UAVs saw service in the 1991 Gulf War.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs demonstrated the possibility of cheaper, more capable fighting-machines, deployable without risk to aircrews.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Initial generations primarily involved surveillance aircraft, but some carried armaments, such as the General Atomics MQ-1 Predator, that launched AGM-114 Hellfire air-to-ground missiles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] CAPECON, a European Union project to develop UAVs, ran from 1 May 2002 to 31 December 2005.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] As of 2012, the United States Air Force (USAF) employed 7,494 UAVs – almost one in three USAF aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The Central Intelligence Agency also operated UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] By 2013 at least 50 countries used UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] China, Iran, Israel, Pakistan, Turkey, and others designed and built their own varieties.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The use of drones has continued to increase.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Due to their wide proliferation, no comprehensive list of UAV systems exists.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 2006, the United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allowed the usage of unmanned aerial vehicles inside civilian airspace with specific regulations, laying out legal groundwork for consumer drone usage inside the United States.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 2013, DJI released the first model of the Phantom drone, DJI's fully assembled drone model.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Priced at $629, Phantom was an entry-level drone, featuring much more user-friendly experiences than other drones on the market at the time.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The DJI Phantom was considered one of the most influential consumer drone products ever made.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] With its affordability, accessibility, and user-friendly software, it quickly captured the consumer drone market from hobbyists, professionals, and introduced the modern aerial photography drone form factor to the general public.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] By 2017, DJI alone had over 75% of the global consumer drone market share.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 2020, a Kargu 2 drone hunted down and attacked a human target in Libya, according to a report from the UN Security Council's Panel of Experts on Libya, published in March 2021.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This may have been the first time an autonomous weapons system capable of lethal engagement attacked human beings.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Drone technology, including systems such as the Turkish Bayraktar TB2, has been identified as a contributing factor in Azerbaijan's military performance in the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh war against Armenia.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The *Ingenuity* helicopter is an autonomous UAV that operated on Mars from 2021 to 2024.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] As of 2024 the Dragonfly spacecraft is being developed and is aiming to reach and examine Saturn's moon Titan.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Its primary goal is to roam around the surface, expanding the amount of area to be researched previously seen by landers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] As a UAV, Dragonfly allows examination of potentially diverse types of soil.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The drone is set to launch in 2027, and is estimated to take seven more years to reach the Saturnian system.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Miniaturization is also supporting the development of small UAVs, which can be used as an individual system or in a fleet, enabling efficient surveying of large areas in a relatively small amount of time.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The April 2024 Iranian strikes against Israel took place on 13 April 2024 when the Iranian Revolutionary Guard and other groups of the Axis of Resistance launched about 300 drones at Israel, a distance of about 1,500 kilometres.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] According to data from GlobalData, the global military uncrewed aerial systems (UAS) market, which forms a significant part of the UAV industry, is projected to experience a compound annual growth rate of 4.8% over the next decade.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This represents a near doubling in market size, from $12.5 billion in 2024 to an estimated $20 billion by 2034.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The consumer and small UAVs have significantly influenced modern warfare, particularly due to their accessibility and cost and contributed to the development of new offensive and defensive strategies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Both Ukraine and Russia used small consumer drones extensively during the war, which served as a tactical surveillance, strike, and propaganda tools.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Consumer drones were sourced by governments, hobbyists, international donations to Ukraine and Russia to support each side on the battlefield, and were often flown by drone hobbyists recruited by the armed forces.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Consumer drones' affordability, technical capabilities, and reliability contributed to their widespread adoption.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] They were also preferred for their commercial availability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Companies attempted to restrict military usage of consumer product, but effect was limited, as donors and buyers could ship the drones across the border via intermediates and modified their software to circumnavigate the restrictions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In Ukraine, small commercial UAVs and FPV drones had become an ubiquitous and critical part of the war.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Crewed and uncrewed aircraft of the same type generally have recognizably similar physical components.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The main exceptions are the cockpit and environmental control system or life-support systems.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Some UAVs carry payloads (such as a camera) that weigh considerably less than an adult human, and as a result, can be considerably smaller.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Though they carry heavy payloads, weaponized military UAVs are lighter than their crewed counterparts with comparable armaments.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Small civilian UAVs have no life-critical systems, and can thus be built out of lighter but less sturdy materials and shapes, and can use less robustly tested electronic control systems.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For small UAVs, the quadcopter design has become popular, though this layout is rarely used for crewed aircraft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Miniaturization means that less-powerful propulsion technologies can be used that are not feasible for crewed aircraft, such as small electric motors and batteries.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Control systems for UAVs are often different from crewed craft.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For remote human control, a camera and video link almost always replace the cockpit windows; radio-transmitted digital commands replace physical cockpit controls.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Autopilot software is used on both crewed and uncrewed aircraft, with varying feature sets.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs can be designed in different configurations than manned aircraft, both because there is no need for a cockpit and its windows, and there is no need to optimize for human comfort, although some UAVs are adapted from piloted examples, or are designed for optionally piloted modes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Air safety is also less of a critical requirement for unmanned aircraft, allowing the designer greater freedom to experiment.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Instead, UAVs are typically designed around their onboard payloads and their ground equipment.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These factors have led to a great variety of airframe and motor configurations in UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For conventional flight, the flying wing and blended wing body offer light weight combined with low drag and stealth, and are popular configurations for many use cases.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Larger types which carry a variable payload are more likely to feature a distinct fuselage with a tail for stability, control and trim, although the wing configurations in use vary widely.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For uses that require vertical flight or hovering, the tailless quadcopter requires a relatively simple control system and is common for smaller UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Multirotor designs with 6 or more rotors is more common with larger UAVs, where redundancy is prioritized.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Traditional internal combustion and jet engines remain in use for drones requiring long range.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] However, for shorter-range missions electric power has almost entirely taken over.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The distance record for a UAV (built from balsa wood and mylar skin) across the North Atlantic Ocean is held by a gasoline model airplane or UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Manard Hill "in 2003 when one of his creations flew 1,882 miles across the Atlantic Ocean on less than a gallon of fuel" holds this record.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Besides the traditional piston engine, the Wankel rotary engine is used by some drones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This type offers high power output for lower weight, with quieter and more vibration-free running.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Claims have also been made for improved reliability and greater range.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Small drones mostly use lithium-polymer batteries (Li-Po), while some larger vehicles have adopted the hydrogen fuel cell.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Hydrogen-fueled proton-exchange membrane fuel cells for UAVs have the advantages of longer flight duration than rechargeable lithium-ion batteries, of lower total cost of ownership than primary lithium metal batteries and of better stealth than heat engines.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The energy density of modern Li-Po batteries is far less than gasoline or hydrogen.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] However, electric motors are cheaper, lighter and quieter.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Complex multi-engine, multi-propeller installations are under development with the goal of improving aerodynamic and propulsive efficiency.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For such complex power installations, battery elimination circuitry (BEC) may be used to centralize power distribution and minimize heating, under the control of a microcontroller unit (MCU).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Flapping-wing ornithopters, imitating birds or insects, have been flown as microUAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Their inherent stealth recommends them for spy missions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Sub-1g microUAVs inspired by flies, albeit using a power tether, have been able to "land" on vertical surfaces.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Other projects mimic the flight of beetles and other insects.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAV computing capability followed the advances of computing technology, beginning with analog controls and evolving into microcontrollers, then system-on-a-chip (SOC) and single-board computers (SBC).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Modern system hardware for UAV control is often called the flight controller (FC), flight controller board (FCB) or autopilot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Common UAV-systems control hardware typically incorporate a primary microprocessor, a secondary or failsafe processor, and sensors such as accelerometers, gyroscopes, magnetometers, and barometers into a single module.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In 2024 EASA agreed on the first certification basis for a UAV flight controller in compliance with the ETSO-C198 for Embention's autopilot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The certification of the UAV flight control systems aims to facilitate the integration of UAVs within the airspace and the operation of drones in critical areas.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Position and movement sensors give information about the aircraft state.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Exteroceptive sensors deal with external information like distance measurements, while exproprioceptive ones correlate internal and external states.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Non-cooperative sensors are able to detect targets autonomously so they are used for separation assurance and collision avoidance.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Degrees of freedom (DOF) refers to both the amount and quality of onboard sensors: 6 DOF implies 3-axis gyroscopes and accelerometers (a typical inertial measurement unit – IMU), 9 DOF refers to an IMU plus a compass, 10 DOF adds a barometer and 11 DOF usually adds a GPS receiver.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In addition to the navigation sensors, the UAV (or UAS) can be also equipped with monitoring devices such as: RGB, multispectral, hyper-spectral cameras or LiDAR, which may allow providing specific measurements or observations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAV actuators include digital electronic speed controllers (which control the RPM of the motors) linked to motors/engines and propellers, servomotors (for planes and helicopters mostly), weapons, payload actuators, LEDs and speakers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Modern UAVs run a software stack that ranges from low-level firmware that directly controls actuators, to high level flight planning.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] At the lowest level, firmware directly controls reading from sensors such as an IMU and commanding actuators such as motors.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Control software (often referred to as an autopilot) is responsible for computing actuator speeds given desired vehicle velocity.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Due to its direct interaction with hardware, this software is time-critical and may run on microcontrollers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This software may also handle radio communications, in the case of UAVs that are not autonomous.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] One popular example is the PX4 autopilot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] At the next level, autonomy algorithms compute the desired velocity given higher level goals.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] For example, trajectory optimization may be used to calculate a flight trajectory given a desired goal location.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This software is not necessarily time-critical, and can often run on a single board computer running an operating system such as Linux with relaxed time constraints.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Deep reinforcement learning has also been investigated for UAV flight control, particularly for navigating continuous three-dimensional environments and improving autonomous decision-making.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Similarly, AI-driven automation is increasingly being applied to counter-UAS (C-UAS) systems to reduce operator cognitive load by automatically linking electronic drone detection data with physical tracking cameras for "hands-free" target tracking.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs employ open-loop, closed-loop or hybrid control architectures.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs use a radio for control and exchange of video and other data.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These bi-directional narrowband radio links carried command and control (C&C) and telemetry data about the status of aircraft systems to the remote operator.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In most modern UAV applications, video transmission is required.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] So instead of having separate links for C&C, telemetry and video traffic, a broadband link is used to carry all types of data.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These broadband links can leverage quality of service techniques and carry TCP/IP traffic that can be routed over the internet.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Modern networking standards have explicitly considered drones and therefore include optimizations.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The 5G standard has mandated reduced user plane latency to 1ms while using ultra-reliable and low-latency communications.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAV-to-UAV coordination supported by Remote ID communication technology.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Remote ID messages (containing the UAV coordinates) are broadcast and can be used for collision-free navigation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The level of autonomy in UAVs varies widely.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] One approach to quantifying autonomous capabilities is based on OODA terminology, as suggested by a 2002 US Air Force Research Laboratory report, and used in the table on the right.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Full autonomy is available for specific tasks, such as airborne refueling or ground-based battery switching.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Other functions available or under development include; collective flight, real-time collision avoidance, wall following, corridor centring, simultaneous localization and mapping and swarming, cognitive radio, and machine learning.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] In this context, computer vision can play an important role for automatically ensuring flight safety.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs can be programmed to perform aggressive maneuvers or landing/perching on inclined surfaces, and then to climb toward better communication spots.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Some UAVs can control flight with varying flight modelisation, such as VTOL designs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAVs can also implement perching on a flat vertical surface.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAV endurance is not constrained by the physiological capabilities of a human pilot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Because of their small size, low weight, low vibration and high power-to-weight ratio, Wankel rotary engines are used in many large UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Their engine rotors cannot seize; the engine is not susceptible to shock-cooling during descent and it does not require an enriched fuel mixture for cooling at high power.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] These attributes reduce fuel usage, increasing range or payload.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Proper drone cooling is essential for long-term drone endurance.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Overheating and subsequent engine failure is the most common cause of drone failure.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Hydrogen fuel cells, using hydrogen power, may be able to extend the endurance of small UAVs, up to several hours.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Micro air vehicles endurance is so far best achieved with flapping-wing UAVs, followed by planes and multirotors standing last, due to lower Reynolds number.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Solar-electric UAVs, a concept originally championed by the AstroFlight Sunrise in 1974, have achieved flight times of several weeks.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Solar-powered atmospheric satellites ("atmosats") designed for operating at altitudes exceeding 20 km (12 miles, or 60,000 feet) for as long as five years could potentially perform duties more economically and with more versatility than low Earth orbit satellites.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Likely applications include weather drones for weather monitoring, disaster recovery, Earth imaging and communications.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Electric UAVs powered by microwave power transmission or laser power beaming are other potential endurance solutions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Another application for a high endurance UAV would be to "stare" at a battlefield for a long interval (ARGUS-IS, Gorgon Stare, Integrated Sensor Is Structure) to record events that could then be played backwards to track battlefield activities.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] The delicacy of the British PHASA-35 military drone (at a late stage of development) is such that traversing the first turbulent twelve miles of atmosphere is a hazardous endeavor.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] It has, however, remained on station at 65,000 feet for 24 hours.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Airbus' Zephyr in 2023 has attained 70,000 feet and flown for 64 days; 200 days aimed at.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] This is sufficiently close enough to near-space for them to be regarded in "pseudo-satellites" as regards to their operational capabilities.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Reliability improvements target all aspects of UAV systems, using resilience engineering and fault tolerance techniques.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Individual reliability covers robustness of flight controllers, to ensure safety without excessive redundancy to minimize cost and weight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Besides, dynamic assessment of flight envelope allows damage-resilient UAVs, using non-linear analysis with ad hoc designed loops or neural networks.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] UAV software liability is bending toward the design and certifications of crewed avionics software.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p01] Swarm resilience involves maintaining operational capabilities and reconfiguring tasks given unit failures.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] They can also be used for consumer-related missions like package delivery, as demonstrated by Amazon Prime Air, and critical deliveries of health supplies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] There are numerous civilian, commercial, military, and aerospace applications for UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] As of 2020, seventeen countries have armed UAVs, and more than 100 countries use UAVs in a military capacity.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The first five countries producing domestic UAV designs are the Turkey, United States, China, Israel and Iran.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Top military UAV manufactures are including Baykar, General Atomics, Elbit Systems, Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, Lockheed Martin, Northrop Grumman, Boeing, Turkish Aerospace Industries, IAIO, CASC and CAIG.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] China has established and expanded its presence in military UAV market since 2010.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In the early 2020s, Turkey also established and expanded its presence in the military UAV market.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In the early 2010s, Israeli companies mainly focused on small surveillance UAV systems, and by the number of drones, Israel exported 60.7% (2014) of UAVs on the market while the United States exported 23.9% (2014).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Between 2010 and 2014, there were 439 drones exchanged compared to 322 in the five years previous to that, among these only small fraction of overall trade – just 11 (2.5%) of the 439 are armed drones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The US alone operated over 9,000 military UAVs in 2014; among them more than 7000 are RQ-11 Raven miniature UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Since 2010, Chinese drone companies have begun to export large quantities of drones to the global military market.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Of the 18 countries that are known to have received military drones between 2010 and 2019, the top 12 all purchased their drones from China.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The shift accelerated in the 2020s due to China's advancement in drone technologies and manufacturing, compounded by market demand from the Russo-Ukrainian war and the Gaza war.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] For intelligence and reconnaissance missions, the inherent stealth of micro UAV flapping-wing ornithopters, imitating birds or insects, offers potential for covert surveillance and makes them difficult targets to bring down.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Unmanned surveillance and reconnaissance aerial vehicle are used for reconnaissance, attack, demining, and target practice.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Since the start of the Russo-Ukrainian war, a dramatic increase in UAV development took place with Ukraine creating the Brave1 platform to promote rapid development of innovative systems.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] By 2025, Ukraine and Russia had both established their own dedicated UAV military commands, named the Unmanned Systems Forces.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Unlike Russia, Ukraine has been able to innovatively employ UAVs to deliver equipment like flexible medical stretchers or electric bicycles to help evacuate wounded soldiers from combat.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Both militaries have made rapid progress in drone innovation whereby new developments happen in weeks instead of years due to the frequent interaction between military end users and defense contractors shortening feedback cycles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Reverse-engineering drone designs and strategies are also commonplace as shown by examples like Ukraine copying Russia's Molniya fixed-wing drones and Russia employing drone motherships equipped with Starlink.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The 2026 Iran war saw the crucial need for multiple countries to reevaluate their anti-drone capabilities in the wake of multiple missile and drone strikes that successfully hit military and civilian targets like airports, ports, and energy infrastructure throughout the Persian Gulf.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] During the war, Iranian utilized mass-produced thousands of cheap drones like the Shahed-136 and missiles like the Fateh-110 which turned the Straits of Hormuz into a shooting gallery when Western air-defense missile stocks ran low.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The costs of neutralizing a Shahed-136 was estimated at US$20,000 to US$50,000 compared to the expensive PATRIOT, THAAD, and Arrow-3 interceptor missiles which range from US$3 to US$12 million.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The war created a surge in demand for Ukrainian interceptor drones and anti-drone expertise in the Gulf countries, Israel, Europe, and the United States.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] FPV-based interceptors like the P1-Sun, STING, JEDI, Octopus, and Shvidun can reach speeds of up to 300 km/h and cost as low as around US$1,000, thereby providing a cost-effective anti-drone solution as part of a multi-layered air defense network.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The civilian (commercial and general) drone market is dominated by Chinese companies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Chinese manufacturer DJI alone had 74% of the civil market share in 2018, with no other company accounting for more than 5%.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The companies continue to hold over 70% of global market share by 2023, despite under increasing scrutinies and sanctions from the United States.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The US Interior Department grounded its fleet of DJI drones in 2020, while the Justice Department prohibited the use of federal funds for the purchase of DJI and other foreign-made UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] DJI is followed by American company 3D Robotics, Chinese company Yuneec, Autel Robotics, and French company Parrot.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In 2025, Chinese drone companies held 90% of the global UAV market share, with DJI accounting 80 percent of the world market.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] As of May 2021, 873,576 UAVs had been registered with the US FAA, of which 42% were categorized as commercial and 58% as recreational.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] 2018 NPD point to consumers increasingly purchasing drones with more advanced features with 33 percent growth in both the $500+ and $1000+ market segments.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The civil UAV market is relatively new compared to the military one.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Companies are emerging in both developed and developing nations at the same time.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Many early-stage startups have received support and funding from investors, as is the case in the United States, and from government agencies, as is the case in India.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Some universities offer research and training programs or degrees.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Private entities also provide online and in-person training programs for both recreational and commercial UAV use.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Consumer drones are widely used by police and military organizations worldwide because of the cost-effective nature of consumer products.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Since 2018, the Israeli military have used DJI UAVs for light reconnaissance missions.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] DJI drones have been used by Chinese police in Xinjiang since 2017 and American police departments nationwide since 2018.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Both Ukraine and Russia used commercial DJI drones extensively during the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] These civilian DJI drones were sourced by governments, hobbyists, international donations to Ukraine and Russia to support each side on the battlefield, and were often flown by drone hobbyists recruited by the armed forces.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The prevalence of DJI drones was attributable to their market dominance, affordability, high performance, and reliability.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones are ideally suited to capturing aerial shots in photography and cinematography, and are widely used for this purpose.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Small drones avoid the need for precise coordination between pilot and cameraman, with the same person taking on both roles.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Larger drones equipped with professional cinema cameras usually have a drone pilot and a camera operator who controls the camera angle and lens.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] For example, the AERIGON cinema drone, used in film production, is operated by two people.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones provide access to dangerous, remote, or otherwise inaccessible sites.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Agricultural drones have been used to help build sustainable agriculture all over the world leading to a new generation of agriculture.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In this context, there is a proliferation of innovations in both tools and methodologies which allow precise description of vegetation state and also may help to precisely distribute nutrients, pesticides or seeds over a field.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The use of UAVs is also being investigated to help detect and fight wildfires, whether through observation or launching pyrotechnic devices to start backfires.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs are also now widely used to survey wildlife such as nesting seabirds, seals and even wombat burrows.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones are also used in nighttime displays for artistic and advertising purposes, with the main benefits being that they are safer, quieter, and better for the environment than fireworks.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] They can replace or be an adjunct to fireworks displays to reduce the financial burden of festivals.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In addition they can complement fireworks due to the ability for drones to carry them, creating new forms of artwork in the process.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones can also be used for racing, either with or without VR functionality.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UASs or UAVs offer a great advantage for environmental monitoring to generate a new generation of survey at very-high or ultra-high resolution both in space and time.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] This enables integration between satellites data and field-based monitoring.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] This has stimulated a huge number of activities in order to enhance the description of natural and agricultural ecosystems.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] These activities can be completed with different measurements, such as photogrammetry, thermography, multispectral images, 3D field scanning, gas detectors, and normalized difference vegetation index maps.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs have become a widely used tool for studying geohazards such as landslides.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Various sensors, including radar, optical, and thermal, can be mounted on UAVs to monitor different properties.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs enable the capture of images of various landslide features, such as transverse, radial, and longitudinal cracks, ridges, scarps, and surfaces of rupture, even in inaccessible areas of the sliding mass.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Moreover, processing the optical images captured by UAVs also allows for the creation of point clouds and 3D models, from which these properties can be derived.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Comparing point clouds obtained at different times allows for the detection of changes caused by landslide deformation.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones are increasingly finding their application in humanitarian aid and disaster relief, where they are used for a wide range of applications such as delivering food, medicine and essential items to remote areas or image mapping before and following disasters.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Police can use drones for applications such as search and rescue and traffic monitoring.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs may help in the discovery of new or reevaluation of known mineral deposits to meet the demand for raw materials such as critical raw metals (e.g. cobalt, nickel), rare earths and battery minerals.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] By employing a suite of sensors (e.g. spectral imaging, Lidar, magnetics, gamma-ray spectroscopy), and similar to those used in environmental monitoring, UAV-based data can produce maps of geological surface and subsurface features, contributing to more efficient and targeted mineral exploration.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs can threaten airspace security in numerous ways, including unintentional collisions or other interference with other aircraft, deliberate attacks or by distracting pilots or flight controllers.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The first incident of a drone-airplane collision occurred in mid-October 2017 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Unauthorized UAV flights into or near major airports have prompted extended shutdowns of commercial flights.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Drones caused significant disruption at Gatwick Airport during December 2018, needing the deployment of the British Army.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In the United States, flying close to a wildfire is punishable by a maximum $25,000 fine.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Nonetheless, in 2014 and 2015, firefighting air support in California was hindered on several occasions, including at the Lake Fire and the North Fire.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In response, California legislators introduced a bill that would allow firefighters to disable UAVs which invaded restricted airspace.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The FAA later required registration of most UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] By 2017, drones were being used to drop contraband into prisons.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The interest in UAVs cybersecurity has been raised greatly after the Predator UAV video stream hijacking incident in 2009, where Islamic militants used cheap, off-the-shelf equipment to stream video feeds from a UAV.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Another risk is the possibility of hijacking or jamming a UAV in flight.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Several security researchers have made public some vulnerabilities in commercial UAVs, in some cases even providing full source code or tools to reproduce their attacks.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] A challenging issue is handling aerial drone technology within privacy laws.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Many UAVs have been loaded with dangerous payloads, and/or crashed into targets.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Payloads have included or could include explosives, chemical, radiological or biological hazards.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] UAVs with generally non-lethal payloads could possibly be hacked and put to malicious purposes.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Counter-UAV systems (C-UAS), from detection to electronic warfare to UAVs designed to destroy other UAVs, are in development and being deployed by states to counter this threat.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Such developments have occurred despite the difficulties.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Rogers stated in a 2017 interview to A&T, "There is a big debate out there at the moment about what the best way is to counter these small UAVs, whether they are used by hobbyists causing a bit of a nuisance or in a more sinister manner by a terrorist actor".
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The malicious use of UAVs has led to the development of counter unmanned air system (C-UAS) technologies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Automatic tracking and detection of UAVs from commercial cameras have become accurate thanks to the development of deep learning based machine learning algorithms.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] It is also possible to automatically identify UAVs across different cameras with different viewpoints and hardware specification with re-identification methods.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Commercial systems such as the Aaronia AARTOS have been installed on major international airports.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Once a UAV is detected, it can be countered with kinetic force (missiles, projectiles or another UAV) or by non-kinetic force (laser, microwaves, communications jamming).
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Anti-aircraft missile systems such as the Iron Dome are also being enhanced with C-UAS technologies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Utilising a smart UAV swarm to counter one or more hostile UAVs is also proposed.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] A variety of counter-UAS (C-UAS) systems have been developed globally to address the growing threat of small and tactical UAVs.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] These include multi-layered approaches combining radar, electro-optical sensors, radio frequency detection, and jamming technologies.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Among them are systems developed by Elbit Systems, such as the ReDrone™ suite, which includes both fixed and portable configurations for detection and mitigation of drones in civilian and military environments.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The Red Sky 2 system, also developed by Elbit, integrates multiple sensors and effectors and is designed to protect strategic sites from low-altitude aerial threats.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Other developers, such as AirSight, specialize in the software and systems integration layer of C-UAS, utilizing AI and machine learning to analyze sensor data for drone detection and threat assessment in complex environments, as demonstrated by the launch of their AirGuard V3.18 system.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Regulatory bodies around the world are developing unmanned aircraft system traffic management solutions to better integrate UAVs into airspace.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The use of unmanned aerial vehicles is becoming increasingly regulated by the civil aviation authorities of individual countries.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Regulatory regimes can differ significantly according to drone size and use.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) began exploring the use of drone technology as far back as 2005, which resulted in a 2011 report.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] France was among the first countries to set a national framework based on this report and larger aviation bodies such as the FAA and the EASA quickly followed suit.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] In April 2026, China has introduced strict rules for recreational and civilian drones, require registration, IDs, real name, permit and real time monitoring.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] Beijing enacted near a total ban, limiting sales, transport and flights within the city.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The regulation aim to ensure safety, manage low altitude airspace and address security.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The implementation of the Class Identification Label serves a crucial purpose in the regulation and operation of drones.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The label is a verification mechanism designed to confirm that drones within a specific class meet the rigorous standards set by administrations for design and manufacturing.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] These standards are necessary to ensure the safety and reliability of drones in various industries and applications.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] By providing this assurance to customers, the Class Identification Label helps to increase confidence in drone technology and encourages wider adoption across industries.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] This, in turn, contributes to the growth and development of the drone industry and supports the integration of drones into society.
[src:drone-uav-systems/unmanned-aerial-vehicle-p02] The export of UAVs or technology capable of carrying a 500 kg payload at least 300 km is restricted in many countries by the Missile Technology Control Regime.
